title: For Sale:  WW-II Smith & Wesson .38 S&W Canadian Lend-Lease “Victory” .38 Special $400
location: Near Ft. Benning, GA, Phenix City, Alabama
postcontent:
This revolver has a 5" barrel (measured from cylinder to muzzle), a parkerized finish, and smooth walnut grips. Included is a U.S. marked russet brown leather holster ($25.00 value)

Marked on butt:
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)
- GHD and “Ordinance Bomb” (From approximately April 1942 to about May 1943 the acceptance mark of Ordnance Officer Guy H. Drewry is found on the butt)

Marked on frame top strap:
- traces of UNITED STATES PROPERTY

Marked on left frame:
- “British Broad Arrow” /|\ in a "C" (denotes Canadian military property)
- “crossed pennants” with M (?) on left cross; 2 under cross; and B to right of cross (The crossed pennants were the military proof, indicating that unlike many other Lend Lease guns, this gun was actually used by the Canadian British Armed Forces)
- “Crown” over BNP (the BNP for Birmingham Nitro Proof, the normal British post-1955 commercial proof, put on when the gun was sold out of army stores)
- CAL. .38 SPECIAL

Stamped on the frame under the crane:
- M4
- 78699

Stamped on the crane:
- 78699

Cylinder marked with:
- “Crown” over BNP six (6) times (once for each chamber)
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)

Marked on right frame:
- S&W Trade Mark Logo
- MADE IN U.S.A.

Marked on top of barrel:
- SMITH & WESSON SPRINGFIELD MASS U.S.A.
- PATENTED FEB 6 06 SEPT 14 09 DEC 19 14.

Marked on left barrel:
- SMITH & WESSON
- “Crown” over BNP
- .38 .767 (for .38 cal. and .767 is the cartridge length in inches)
- 3 ½ TONS (this is the proof pressure, - the British didn't use “psi” for their pressure testing)

Marked on right barrel:
- 38 S&W CTG

Marked on under barrel:
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)

Grips marked on inside:
- 505681

The Smith & Wesson Victory Model was born from a war time request by the U.S. Military to supplement their issued sidearms with quickly tooled up civilian handguns. During World War 2, the U.S. Military sent over 570,000 of these pistols to both British and British Commonwealth forces. The V serial number range did not begin until 24 April 1942. All previous guns, both 38 S&W (or British .38/200) and .38 Spl, were serial numbered in the K frame range up to 999,999 and do NOT have the V prefix serial number and are, therefore, NOT considered Victory models. As production neared one million, S&W considered adding an A prefix, as their SN numbering machine was only capable of stamping six digits. Someone suggested instead to make the prefix “V” for Victory, and thus this model was named the "Victory Model.” (Later, the hammer block safety was introduced at V769,000 when the prefix became SV. The end of war Victory model was SV811119, after which the prefix became S and the serial numbers continued, but these were no longer Victory models.)

… Most Lend-Lease Victory Model revolvers were originally chambered for the .38 S&W (or British .38/200) and many of these were later rechambered to fire the more popular .38 Special ammunition. A lot of these were refurbished by Parker Hale, Ltd., or Cogswell & Harrison, - but not all of them, - which leads to various grades of quality in the rechamberings. One issue to be aware of is that rechambering of 38 S&W (or British .38/200) cylinders to .38 Special results in oversized chambers which allow cases to possibly bulge or split. This does not affect accuracy or performance, but it does prevent the brass from being reloaded for use again. (NOTE: This gun is NOT rated for +P ammo.) I took THIS revolver to the Range the other day, and shot a group of surplus M41 FMJ Ball ammo at 10 yards, and the group was low at 6 o'clock, but five shots made a single jagged hole that was smaller than a Quarter, - and I dropped one shot (my fault, not the guns)  I also shot shot some vintage .38 S&W with similar results. … Based upon it's accuracy, and since this gun is professionally stamped on the frame “CAL. .38 SPECIAL” it is my assumption that the rechambering of this pistol was done by a competent armory.

I also have a box of 50 rounds of Winchester LRN .38 S&W ammo for this gun that I will sell "with" the pistol for $35. if you're interested.

title: For Sale:  Lowered $ M96 Swedish Mauser 1899 Reduced Price Again!
postcontent:
1899 Swedish Mauser M96

Manufactured in 1899, this is a beautiful Model 1896 Swedish Mauser manufactured by Carl Gustafs Stads Gevärsfaktori. This Pre-WWI rifle is an excellent example of the finely machined weaponry of the time and shows battle usage. There are several things that make this firearm very special.

It has matching numbers throughout, including the buttplate, magazine door, barrel ring, bayonet mount, bolt release, bolt, bolt knob, safety and receiver. The serial number is o.g. 12810 and makes this one of the earliest ones built, about mid-year in 1899.

This is an older import and does not have any stamping on the barrel showing the importer. Most of the guns you find these days have this stamping, and in my opinion detract from the value.

It has the original stock medallion (showing bore condition and size), original rings and cleaning rod. Crown Cartouche stamping is prevalant throughout, including marks on the stock, bayonet mount, barrel ring, floorplate, rear sight and reciever.The threaded muzzel is in fine shape and the adjustable front blade sight is present. It has "0" stamped on the mount and blade, presumably a sighters inspection stamping.

The Micro-Adjustable rear sight is a rare option and this one is perfect. It is not bent, rusted or worn out, and shows original bluing on the spring.

Condition is very good for it’s 113 year age with all metal surfaces showing a nice patina and the wood having a lot of usage marks. Fit between the metal and wood is superb, indicating the stock has never been refinished. The bore is bright and shiny with deep rifiling present. After removing the cosmoline in 1980, I fired this weapon a total of 4 rounds, and it function flawlessly. It has been either hanging above my door, or in my closet ever since.

All in all, this fine piece of military history is an unmarked and unmolested perfect example of turn of the century Northern European craftmanship.

$599 OBO or Trades...make me an offer...who knows?
Call 7oh1-59O-87O8 and leave a message if you are interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Excam Tanfoglio BTA-90 9mm
postcontent:
For sale or trade is my Tanfoglio BTA-90 - for those not familiar with them, the TZ-90 & TA-90 series guns were imported during the 80's to fill in for CZ-75's that were banned from being imported.  The BTA's were the compact version (for concealed carry, etc.)  The current Tanfoglio importer is EAA.  The EAA version of this gun is called the Witness Compact.  There are some differences, primarily in the way of a full beavertail.  Otherwise very little has changed with them other than the importer.  It is also similar (same frame) as the Baby Eagle pistols.

It is a very solid & accurate gun and is in good shape.  It deviates from the original CZ-75's with the decocker (Tanfoglio was the first to do this on the browning hi-power platform).  

I've put roughly 300 rounds through it, of all kinds of different ammo.  It seems to handle russian steel-cased stuff no problem other than a few light strikes on TulAmmo particularly (shitty ammo, not the gun's fault), but no FTF's or FTE's.  It handled Blazer & Blazer Brass, RWS (Geco), & Federal FMJ's just fine.  It was unfired as far as I could tell when I bought it half a year ago. 

Comes with one 13 round magazine and a padded range case (holds 4 spare mags, a box or two of ammo, & the gun).

**UPDATE**

Due to people jerking me around, I'm going to be more specific.  If you are going to expect me to lower the price because you are hours away and will expend gas money to meet up or purchase this firearm, don't contact me.  If you aren't interested, don't tell me you are, make offers, and then just disappear off the face of the planet, or keep lowering the price until I'm pretty much giving it away.  Also, I don't appreciate the condescending crap where you chuckleheads are acting like you are doing me a favor.  Go into a gun store and see how far such a flippant attitude will get you.  It scares me that some of the people I've been corresponding with own or are attempting to own firearms.  The level of stupidity I've encountered is destroying my faith in humanity.  I'm willing to haggle price-wise, just talk to me.  The worst is I can say no.  I'm open to all trades at this point as long as you aren't asking me to pay cash on top of a trade of equal or lesser value.  **End Rant**

postcontent:
KEELY ENTERPRISES

NO credit card fees!!

Stag Model 2 AR-15

NOTE*** All above listed accessory prices are installed and only valid with rifle purchase. Please contact us if you have any questions. 

ABOUT US
We are a new FFL dealer located in Central Ohio. For years we have been selling holsters and other various accessories, but we are now excited to begin selling to you all of your favorite AR style rifles and semi-auto pistols. If you are looking for a particular gun that we do not have listed, please feel free to contact us and we will try our best to help you find it.

OUR POLICIES
Payment
Visa, MasterCard, Discover credit cards accepted with no additional fees. Payment can be made through the auction sites shopping cart, if available. If not, we will send a link to our website's Auction/classified Listing Payment link, so that you can make a secure credit card payment.
NO ADDITIONAL FEES for credit card payments. In fact, we encourage it because it is safer and more secure for all parties involved 
Ohio residents will be charged 7.0% sales tax

Transactions requiring FFL's
Please have your FFL dealer fax or email a signed, legible copy within 5 days of the purchase to us
Make sure the FFL holder includes your name on the fax or email
We will include a copy of our FFL with the shipment

Shipping
We will ship handguns via USPS Priority mail, other items may vary
All shipments of firearms will be insured and tracking number will be provided
Shipping fee for rifles will be $30, other items will be marked individually 
Will not ship to  MD, NY, Washington DC, or other areas where items are not legal to own
Shipping price is for lower 48, extra fee for Alaska and Hawaii
It is the buyer's responsibility to make sure the item purchased is legal in their area
We WILL ship to CA if the item is on the approved list and meets the state's requirements. Shipping times may increase by a couple days due to the additional paperwork required.

Warranties/Returns
New firearms carry the warranty from the manufacturer
Used firearms are sold As Is
If for some reason you believe the item you received is not as we represented, please contact us. We want you to be happy with your purchase!

Trades
We do not routinely accept trades, but on rare occasions we will consider them
Terms will be worked out through email/phone prior to any shipments
Once terms are agreed upon by both parties, we will send a copy of our FFL to your licensed dealer. Your dealer will ship your firearm to us. Once we receive your firearm, we will then ship the agreed upon product to your FFL dealer.

Questions
We strongly encourage you to contact us at if you have any questions regarding an item you may wish to purchase. We want to make sure you have confidence in your purchase.
Our products are also for sale locally and we reserve the right to end the sale/auction early as long as there are no bids over any set reserve price.
New gun listings may use stock photos. Serial numbers in pictures may not be the same as the gun shipped.


THANKS AND HAPPY BUYING!!
